[[File:Sagkrakk.jpg|thumb|]] A '''sawbuck''' is a device for holding wood so that it may be cut into pieces.<ref>{{cite journal|title='buck' n7. def. 1., 'sawbuck' def. 1.|work=Oxford English Dictionary|edition=Second on CD-ROM (v. 4.0) |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2009}}</ref> Easily made in the field from rough material, it consists of an "X" form at each end which are joined by cross bars below the intersections of the X's. The stock to be cut is placed in the V's formed above the intersections of the X's.
A sawbuck is very simple to build. The five "V" sawbuck was designed with 10 vertical {{convert|4|ft|m|abbr=in|order=flip|adj=mid|-long}} [[Lumber#North American softwoods|2×4s]], and four horizontal, {{convert|5|ft|m|abbr=in|order=flip|adj=mid|-long}} [[Lumber#North American softwoods|2×6s]], secured with {{convert|3.5|in|abbr=in|order=flip}} wood screws. It was designed this way in order to cut two or more smaller pieces ({{convert|2|-|4|ft|1|abbr=in|order=flip|disp=or}} in length) of firewood in rapid succession. A sawbuck should be heavy enough to negate any kickback from the saw while cutting. Building a sawbuck that is too light could result in injury as it may tip over while cutting, especially with a chainsaw.{{cn|date=May 2015}}
In Canada and Britain, and the United States, a sawbuck is called a ''[[sawhorse]]'',{{cn|date=May 2015}} although this term also refers to a similar device used (often in pairs) to support wood planks.{{cn|date=May 2015}}
==$10== "Sawbuck" is also a slang term for a [[United States ten-dollar bill|U.S. $10 bill]], derived from the similarity between the shape of a sawbuck device and the [[Roman numeral]] X (10), which formerly appeared on $10 bills.<ref>{{cite web|website=Investor Words|title=Sawbuck|accessdate=May 10, 2015|url=http://www.investorwords.com/6657/sawbuck.html}}</ref> A "double sawbuck" is a twenty dollar bill.
